article.description:
Erin Buescher had a career-high 25
points and nine rebounds as the Sacramento Monarchs built a big
early lead and beat the Minnesota Lynx 87-76 Thursday night.
article.headline: Buescher scores 25 as Monarchs roll over Lynx
article.linkText: Buescher scores 25 as Monarchs roll over Lynx
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Erin Buescher made the most of her
first start in five years -- against the team she played for back
then.

Buescher had a career-high 25 points and nine rebounds as the
Sacramento Monarchs built a big early lead and beat the Minnesota
Lynx 87-78 Thursday night.

Buescher made the most of her first start since 2001 -- when she
was a rookie with the Lynx. Replacing Rebekkah Brunson in the
starting lineup, Buescher had eight of Sacramento's first 13 points
and surpassed her previous career high of 18 by the midpoint of the
third quarter.

"It's a little ironic that was (five) years ago, oh my gosh, I
feel like I'm still in high school," Buescher said. "I was
surprised to be starting. I think he (Sacramento coach John
Whisenant) was trying to shake things up, get more consistency."

Using her speed and quickness inside against the less athletic
Lynx, she shot 8-for-15 from the field and 9-for-14 on free throws.

"She is by far the most improved player in our league this
year," Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "She keeps it
simple. She plays with a lot of energy and works so hard."

Yolanda Griffith scored 12 points and had eight rebounds for the
Monarchs (8-7), who didn't let Minnesota get closer than seven
points in the fourth quarter. Ticha Penicheiro had 11 points and
DeMya Walker added 10.

Kristen Mann and Svetlana Abrosimova both scored 16 points for
Minnesota (5-10), which has dropped four straight, six of seven and
fell to 1-7 on the road. Adrian Williams added 11 points and 13
rebounds.

Lynx rookie Seimone Augustus had her second-worst scoring game
of the season. The WNBA's second-leading scorer had 13 points on
5-for-12 shooing, her lowest total since scoring seven points
against San Antonio on June 16.

"Credit their defense, they did a good job on Seimone,"
McConnell Serio said. "We played last night, fatigue was possibly
a factor. I thought the shots she took were good shots. She missed
ones she usually makes."

Guarded by the athletic Hamchetou Maiga-Ba for much of the game,
Augustus was scoreless until she made a difficult step-back jumper
at the 7:20 mark of the second quarter.

"She's the No. 1 pick (in the draft), a great player,"
Maiga-Ba said. "I can't keep her from scoring. But you need to
limit her touches, that's what I was trying to do. When she has the
ball she's tough to control."

The Lynx were sluggish early and got in a deep hole, falling
behind by 20 at one point in the first quarter.

Minnesota committed nine turnovers and Sacramento used a 23-1
run to take a 25-9 lead after the opening quarter.

"Coach showed us the stats and we messed up in the first
quarter," Augustus said. "They came out strong and we didn't have
any energy or any intensity. But we came back and fought hard and
that's really all you can do when you come into Sacramento's
house."

Strong outside shooting helped Minnesota pull to 46-35 by
halftime despite Sacramento getting 14 points from Buescher.

Sacramento Kings first-round draft choice Quincy Douby watched
the game in a courtside seat next to new teammate Francisco Garcia.
